message_2:
To encrypt the message "MATH" using the Hill Cipher, we first need to convert the letters to their corresponding numerical values (A=0, B=1, ..., Z=25). So, M=12, A=0, T=19, H=7.

Now, we need to arrange these values into a matrix and multiply it by the key matrix K. Since K is a 2x2 matrix, we will arrange the numerical values of the message into a 2x2 matrix P:

P = 
\begin{bmatrix}
    12 & 19 \\
    0 & 7
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we multiply the key matrix K by the message matrix P:

C = K * P =
\begin{bmatrix}
    2 & 1 \\
    5 & 3
\end{bmatrix}
*
\begin{bmatrix}
    12 & 19 \\
    0 & 7
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
    24 & 45 \\
    60 & 112
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we need to take the resulting matrix C modulo 26:

C (mod 26) =
\begin{bmatrix}
    24 & 45 \\
    60 & 112
\end{bmatrix}
(mod 26) =
\begin{bmatrix}
    24 & 19 \\
    8 & 4
\end{bmatrix}

Finally, we convert the numerical values back to letters: 24=X, 19=T, 8=I, 4=E. So, the encrypted message is "XTIE".
